properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A fast-moving deepening low pressure system is approaching the South Coast of B.C. Strong winds will affect coastal B.C. from midday Friday until Saturday morning. Western sections of Vancouver Island from Zeballos to Sooke are currently under a wind warning. The low is forecast to approach northern Vancouver Island Friday afternoon and then track across Vancouver Island in the evening. Ahead of the low, strong southeast winds up to 70 km/h can be expected over northern sections of east Vancouver Island and Sunshine Coast Friday afternoon. Strong southwest winds of 50 to 70 km/h will affect southern sections of Victoria near Juan De Fuca Strait, such as Esquimalt, downtown Victoria, the Southern Gulf Islands, Inland Vancouver Island, and over southern sections of Metro Vancouver and western Fraser Valley. Behind the track of the low, strong northwest winds up to 70 km/h are expected to sweep through the Strait of Georgia and may affect western sections of Metro Vancouver near the Strait of Georgia. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Total freezing rain amounts: possibly more than to 20 mm over some inland areas, with lesser amounts over southwestern Nova Scotia and along the coast. Location: Nova Scotia. Time span: this morning into this afternoon, and continuing into this evening over some northern regions. Remarks: Freezing rain will gradually change to rain from south to north as temperatures rise above freezing today. Some inland areas may receive total freezing rain accumulations of 20 mm or more from this event. In addition, higher than normal water levels are likely along the Atlantic coast near high tide this evening. Strong southwesterly winds will develop this evening and then diminish somewhat as they shift to northwesterly overnight, as a cold front crossing the province brings snow flurries and a rapid drop to colder temperatures. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and extremely hazardous. Extended and widespread utility outages are possible. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 25 to 40 cm (western Newfoundland) and 15 to 30 cm (Great Northern Peninsula). Maximum wind gusts: east to northeasterly 60 to 80 km/h. Locations: western and northern Newfoundland. Time span: this afternoon until noon Saturday. Remarks: Flurries this morning over western Newfoundland will give way to snow, at times heavy, this afternoon. The heavy snow will spread to the Great Northern Peninsula this evening, in conjunction with strengthening winds resulting in blowing snow. The snow and wind are forecast to begin easing around noon on Saturday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow.
